rComments: I took this course in person in 2021. Really good professor, soft spoken but lecture content is interesting if you like limnology/ecology. The field trip was amazing and as long as you follow along in lectures and take good notes you should do well on the exams. 100% recommend this course, especially if you need one with a lab component.

Took this class with him when it was in-person. Field course component was fun but it took the entire semester to get our marks back for an assignment which made it hard to improve for future assignments since we didn't have an accurate representation for our marks until finals. Passionate about the subject but not clear with his expectations.

I took Freshwater Ecology this semester as we're back in person now after covid and it was my favourite course in my whole undergrad experience. Professor Blais is very approachable and cares about his students - On the trip, he took time to ask every student about what they wanted to do after they graduate and gave advice where he could. loved!!

Had him for fresh water ecology in French , I adored his class. His online lectures were perfect. Short videos no longer than half and hour precise and to point. Exams easy if you listen to lectures . No trip due to Covid. One long lab report . Nice prof

I loved Jules and his class! Freshwater Eco has changed my career path. His test and final were very fair, with both very easy and touch questions. If you study, and know the nutrient cycles, they were easy. Lab reports are long but not hard. A lot of group work for the second trip, but the field trips are incredible! He is soft spoken but so nice!

Awful lecturer, but knowledgeable in his field.  Better off reading from the textbook or slides because that's what he does during the lectures in a quiet voice. Should only be a researcher. Has been teaching a long time and obviously has not improved. Take this class only for the field trips. Doesn't connect with students.

He is not a people person. He seldom looks at the students when teaching, just stares intently at his slides. He speaks very softly. He does know a lot and conveys the material decently well, but if you have a question during class, you shouldn't bother raising your hand because he won't turn around to see it.

The lowest grade in this class was a C+.  In general pretty good prof.  Tips: DO NOT FALL ASLEEP IN CLASS (he rly doesnt like this!!!), start your lab early,  all exams are cumulatif (the final was as much about the first part than the second) and learn notes by heart (read textbook if you have time to add to notes).

He's a smart guy but a terrible lecturer. He whispers, stutters a lot and is generally really hard to follow. Maybe it's just because his French is pretty bad. Maybe he's better in english. He's also very awkward with the students. The field trips were cool though. I wouldn't take this class unless you're really interested in limnology.
